07308nam a22007335i 9780822381129DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20001999ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223811297 a10.1515/97808223811292doi  a(DE-B1597)553809  a(OCoLC)1226678883  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aP306.2b.T65 1999 7aPOL0110002bisacsh00aTokens of Exchange :bThe Problem of Translation in Global Circulations /cLydia H. Liu, Fredric Jameson, Stanley Fish. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2000] 4cÂ©1999  a1 online resource (464 p.) :b22 b&w photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPost-Contemporary Interventions00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction -- tThe Question of Meaning-Value in the Political Economy of the Sign -- tPart I Early Encounters: The Question of (In)commensurability -- tTranslating the Untranslatable: From Copula to IncommensurableWorlds -- tDemystifying Qi: The Politics of Cultural Translation and Interpretation in the Early Jesuit Mission to China -- tAlways Multiple Translation, Or, How the Chinese Language Lost Its Grammar -- tPart II Colonial Circulations: From International Law to the Global Market -- tLegislating the Universal: The Circulation of International Law in the Nineteenth Century -- tJapan's Engagement with International Terms -- tLooting Beijing: 1860, 1900 -- tThe Gramophone in China -- tPart III Science, Medicine, and Cultural Pathologies -- tHandmaids to the Gospel: Lam Qua's Medical Portraiture -- tTranslating Homosexuality: The Discourse of Tongxing'ai in Republican China (1912-1949) -- tTranslating Psychiatry and Mental Health in Twentieth-Century China -- tPart IV Language and the Production of Universal Knowledge -- tThe Bathos of a Universalism: I. A. Richards and His Basic English -- tChinese ''Revolution'' in the Syntax of World Revolution -- tThe Question of Culture in Global English-Language Teaching: A Postcolonial Perspectiv -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe problem of translation has become increasingly central to critical reflections on modernity and its universalizing processes. Approaching translation as a symbolic and material exchange among peoples and civilizations-and not as a purely linguistic or literary matter, the essays in Tokens of Exchange focus on China and its interactions with the West to historicize an economy of translation. Rejecting the familiar regional approach to non-Western societies, contributors contend that "national histories" and "world history" must be read with absolute attention to the types of epistemological translatability that have been constructed among the various languages and cultures in modern times.By studying the production and circulation of meaning as value in areas including history, religion, language, law, visual art, music, and pedagogy, essays consider exchanges between Jesuit and Protestant missionaries and the Chinese between the seventeenth and nineteenth centuries and focus on the interchanges occasioned by the spread of capitalism and imperialism. Concentrating on ideological reciprocity and nonreciprocity in science, medicine, and cultural pathologies, contributors also posit that such exchanges often lead to racialized and essentialized ideas about culture, sexuality, and nation. The collection turns to the role of language itself as a site of the universalization of knowledge in its contemplation of such processes as the invention of Basic English and the global teaching of the English language. By focusing on the moments wherein meaning-value is exchanged in the translation from one language to another, the essays highlight the circulation of the global in the local as they address the role played by historical translation in the universalizing processes of modernity and globalization.The collection will engage students and scholars of global cultural processes, Chinese studies, world history, literary studies, history of science, and anthropology, as well as cultural and postcolonial studies.Contributors. Jianhua Chen, Nancy Chen, Alexis Dudden Eastwood, Roger Hart, Larissa Heinrich, James Hevia, Andrew F. Jones, Wan Shun Eva Lam, Lydia H. Liu, Deborah T. L. Sang, Haun Saussy, Q. S. Tong, Qiong Zhang  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aIntercultural communication. 0aTranslating and interpretingxSocial aspects. 0aTranslating and interpretingzChina. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh1 aDudden, Alexis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Andrew F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFish, Stanley, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSaussy, Haun, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHevia, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJameson, Fredric, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChen, Jianhua, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeinrich, Larissa N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLiu, Lydia H., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLiu, Lydia H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChen, Nancy N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTong, Q. S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZhang, Qiong, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHart, Roger, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSang, Tze-lan Deborah, eco